tz _97ba0 visible" style="padding-bottom:56.34146341463414%"><img src="https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/cybersecurity.jpg?quality=75&amp;strip=all&amp;w=410&amp;h=231" srcSet="https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/cybersecurity.jpg?quality=75&amp;strip=all&amp;w=410&amp;h=231 410w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/cybersecurity.jpg?quality=75&amp;strip=all&amp;w=820&amp;h=462 820w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/cybersecurity.jpg?quality=75&amp;strip=all&amp;w=690&amp;h=388 690w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/cybersecurity.jpg?quality=75&amp;strip=all&amp;w=1380&amp;h=776 1380w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/cybersecurity.jpg?quality=75&amp;strip=all&amp;w=950&amp;h=535 950w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/cybersecurity.jpg?quality=75&amp;strip=all&amp;w=1900&amp;h=1070 1900w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/cybersecurity.jpg?quality=75&amp;strip=all&amp;w=1600&amp;h=900 1600w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/cybersecurity.jpg?quality=75&amp;strip=all&amp;w=3200&amp;h=1800 3200w" sizes="(min-width: 64em) 1600px, (min-width: 48em) 950px, (min-width: 26.5625em) 690px, 410px" alt="" class="" decoding="async"/></div><div class="fafb9 quartz a44ba">AP Photo/Pablo Martinez Monsivais</div></div></figure><div class="_159c3 extra-large quartz f18a2"><div class="_4d056 quartz none ba5c4">BAD BARGAINS</div><h1 class="_21349 quartz none _4ca8e">The new US cybersecurity bill will invade your privacy, but it wonât keep you safe</h1><div class="_9677b quartz c32bd"><div class="_5e088 quartz"><span class="d3284 quartz"><span>By </span><a class="" href="/author/dannyweitzner">Danny Weitzner</a><span class="date b289f"><time dateTime="2015-11-08T12:00:50.000Z">November 8, 2015</time></span></span><h4 class="c24a9 quartz">Director</h4></div></div></div></header><div class="f46e3"><div class="_61c55 quartz"><p class="a1dbe quartz">Â </p><p class="a1dbe quartz">Earlier this week, the White House sought to ease privacy concerns related to theÂ Senateâs <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/28/us/politics/senate-approves-cybersecurity-bill-despite-flaws.html">recent passage</a> of the Cybersecurity Information Sharing Act (CISA). An official saidÂ the bill has aÂ ânumber of very key privacy provisions and use of limitations on how that cybersecurity information can be used,â adding thatÂ the administration would push for further privacy protections.<br><br>Despite these assurances, thereâs reason to be concerned that CISA will sacrifice Americansâ privacyâand it may not even do much to increase online security.</p><div class="b18b1 quartz">Thereâs reason to be concerned that CISA will sacrifice Americansâ privacy.</div><p class="a1dbe quartz">In the wake of massive hacks on <a href="http://qz.com/385742/the-hacked-sony-emails-show-how-silicon-valley-dealmaking-really-works/">Sony</a> and <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/10/us/office-of-personnel-management-hackers-got-data-of-millions.html">government computers</a>, itâs clear the US needs to do more to ward off cyberattacks. CISAÂ aims to reduce online attacks by encouraging companies to share more information about threats with federal agencies. The idea is that the federal government will then analyze emerging threats and share intelligence with at-risk companies.</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">Yet the bill faces vehement opposition from leading tech companies and privacy advocates. <a href="https://www.decidethefuture.org/">Apple, Twitter, LinkedIn, Microsoft, Google, Dropbox, Salesforce and others</a> say that they already share lots of information around the industry, so they donât need the governmentâs help.</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">Meanwhile, privacy advocates argue that the bill works so hard to encourage companies to share information with the government that it cuts corners on privacy, oversight and legal accountability. One major concern is that when companies share information on threatsâsuch as an email that was part of a phishing attack or a file infected with malwareâthose files could contain customersâ personal data. Normally, the government would have to go to court to get a warrant to access this kind of private information. But under the Senate bill, the companies would be absolved of any liability for sharing this private information with law enforcement agencies.</p><div class="b18b1 quartz"> The government will not be as agile or sophisticated as banks in deploying new security technology.</div><p class="a1dbe quartz">Thereâs no doubt Congress has a tough job in this field. Weâre still in the early stages of understanding how best to combat cybersecurity threats. But creating an end-run around existing privacy protections isnât worth it. Thatâs particularly true if thereâs not much benefitâso itâs worth asking how CISAâs approach to cybersecurity compares to proven security strategies in other arenas.</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">Credit-card fraud, for example, causes tens of billions of dollars in losses every year. We manage this risk in two ways. First, federal regulations limit the losses that consumers will have to bear if thieves get ahold of their information. Second, because credit-card companies donât want to get stuck with massive bills, they deploy elaborate technological wizardry to comb through billions of transactions to detect fraud almost instantaneously. When you get a phone call at home in Indiana asking whether you just took out a cash advance at a Las Vegas casino, anti-fraud systems are at work.</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">Now imagine that all suspicious transactions were routed through the Department of the Treasury or the Comptroller of the Currency. We would probably wouldnât want to rely on the feds to make these kinds of fraud assessments<strong>. </strong>The government will not be as agile or sophisticated in deploying new technology as banks that have billions of dollars in potential losses to guard against.</p><div class="b18b1 quartz">Americans have always resisted the idea of an all-knowing government with centralized visibility into citizenâs lives. </div><p class="a1dbe quartz">Nor should there be much enthusiasm for the idea that federal agencies would be allowed to see the details of our private finances. Would those financial details be shared with the IRS or immigration authorities? Or perhaps with the FBI to further the investigation of a completely unrelated crime?</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">Americans have always resisted the idea of an all-knowing government with centralized visibility into citizenâs lives. But CISA proposes just this kind of centralized approach to risk management.</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">The bill also empowers companies to launch their own defensive measures against cyber attackers. For example, companies could create troves of fake data to lure adversaries into wasting their energy trying to break into useless targets.</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">But apply the same logic to the way we manage speeding in residential neighborhoods. Can you imagine if we empowered private citizens to erect their own speed bumps on the road? Suppose those speed bumps are poorly designed, and a driver whose car gets damaged jumps out and starts a fight with the neighbors who installed them. In the same way, these defensive cyber measures could accidentally be directed at a benign target. Or suppose the poorly-designed speed bump causes an accident in which the speeding truck dumps toxic cargo. We have very little experience with the escalation patterns that defensive measures might engender.</p><div class="b18b1 quartz">The bill waives privacy and wiretapping laws to encourage companies to monitor their own networks</div><p class="a1dbe quartz">Perhaps most alarmingly, the bill waives privacy and wiretapping laws to encourage companies to monitor their own networks. Personal data will inevitably be mixed in with threat information that companies share with the government.</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">It would be nice to believe that a well-meaning company would work hard to avoid turning over personal data to the government. But that fact is that the bill excuses companies from liability for violating privacy laws except in the most extreme cases. So the incentives are stacked against privacy.</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">Moreover, under CISA, we will have sharply limited the independent judicial oversight that has been so important to protecting privacy. At a time when there is growing distrust of how both companies and governments handle personal data, this bill is a big step in the wrong direction.</p><div class="b18b1 quartz">It may be a mistake to believe that government agencies will be better at spotting attacks than Amazon, MasterCard or Google.</div><p class="a1dbe quartz">As Congress works to finalize CISA, it would be a mistake to feel that this approach is the only option to protect our security. The Federal Trade Commission is becoming increasingly active in requiring that companies follow industry standard security measures when holding consumersâ personal data. The threat of fines or lawsuits can also encourage companies to follow reasonable security practices. And there are numerous federal agencies that already have legal authority to regulate companies in our most vulnerable sectors, including banks, health, nuclear power and the electric grid.</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">We have a lot of work to do in order to make American society more resistant to cyber threats. But it may be a mistake to believe that government agencies will be better at spotting attacks than Amazon, MasterCard or Google. Letâs not put our faith in overly-centralized solutions that compromise our privacy.</p><p class="a1dbe quartz"><em>We welcome your ideas at <a href="mailto:ideas@qz.com">ideas@qz.com</a>.</em></p><p class="a1dbe quartz">Â </p></div><aside class="_81b22 _06156"></aside></div><footer class="_4a48d"><div class="_61cca e970b"><div class="_3b7f8"><div class="_5f5af"><a href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=https%3A%2F%2Fqz.com%2F543692%2F&amp;text=The%20new%20US%20cybersecurity%20bill%20will%20invade%20your%20privacy%2C%20but%20it%20won%E2%80%99t%20keep%20you%20safe&amp;via=qz" class="_1a7c0 quartz article twitter" target="_blank" rel="noopener" title="Share via twitter"><svg width="25" height="20" viewBox="0 0 25 20"><path d="M22.053 3.122A5.006 5.006 0 0 0 24.308.364c-.992.573-2.094.987-3.255 1.211A5.212 5.212 0 0 0 17.305 0c-2.835 0-5.129 2.232-5.129 4.986 0 .388.045.77.13 1.134A14.71 14.71 0 0 1 1.737.913a4.884 4.884 0 0 0-.693 2.507c0 1.727.91 3.252 2.286 4.146a5.207 5.207 0 0 1-2.324-.623l-.001.064c0 2.413 1.767 4.427 4.114 4.888-.43.112-.884.172-1.352.172-.33 0-.653-.033-.965-.092.653 1.983 2.548 3.421 4.792 3.462a10.484 10.484 0 0 1-6.37 2.131c-.414 0-.822-.025-1.223-.07a14.8 14.8 0 0 0 7.86 2.239c9.435 0 14.594-7.59 14.594-14.176 0-.219-.004-.435-.013-.647A10.154 10.154 0 0 0 25 2.338c-.92.396-1.908.665-2.947.784z" style="fill:var(--color-ui,000)" fill-rule="evenodd"></path></svg></a><a href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Fqz.com%2F543692%2Famericans-should-probably-be-more-freaked-out-about-that-new-cybersecurity-bill%2F&amp;caption=qz.com%20%7C%20By%20Danny%20Weitzner" class="_1a7c0 quartz article facebook" target="_blank" rel="noopener" title="Share via facebook"><svg width="25" height="25" viewBox="0 0 25 25"><path d="M1.379 0A1.38 1.38 0 0 0 0 1.38v22.241C0 24.384.62 25 1.379 25h11.779v-9.21h-3.29v-3.948h3.29V8.763c.195-3.227 2.166-4.987 5.047-4.987 1.38 0 2.566.103 2.848.15V7.3h-1.936c-1.566 0-1.868.743-1.868 1.838l.021 2.752 3.783-.048-.658 3.947h-3.29L17.25 25h6.371A1.38 1.38 0 0 0 25 23.621V1.381A1.383 1.383 0 0 0 23.62 0H1.379z" style="fill:var(--color-ui,000)" fill-rule="evenodd"></path></svg></a><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/shareArticle?mini=true&am