tlight Concealments LLC roughly $22,000 since June 2018 for âvideo recording and reproducing equipment.â ICE paid out about $28,000 to Cowboy Streetlight Concealments over the same period of time.</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">Itâs unclear where the DEA and ICE streetlight cameras have been installed, or where the next deployments will take place. ICE offices in Dallas, Houston, and San Antonio have provided funding for recent acquisitions from Cowboy Streetlight Concealments; the DEAâs most recent purchases were funded by the agencyâs Office of Investigative Technology, which is located in Lorton, Virginia.</p><figure class="_43d66 aligncenter _68dc3 quartz _451d8"><div class="_5fc35 quartz"><div class="_83471 _97ba0 visible" style="padding-bottom:82.98387096774194%"><img src="https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Cowboy-Streetlight-Concealments-FPDS.png?w=620&amp;strip=all&amp;quality=75" srcSet="https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Cowboy-Streetlight-Concealments-FPDS.png?w=350&amp;strip=all&amp;quality=75 350w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Cowboy-Streetlight-Concealments-FPDS.png?w=700&amp;strip=all&amp;quality=75 700w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Cowboy-Streetlight-Concealments-FPDS.png?w=620&amp;strip=all&amp;quality=75 620w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Cowboy-Streetlight-Concealments-FPDS.png?w=1240&amp;strip=all&amp;quality=75 1240w" sizes="(min-width: 48em) 620px, 100vw" alt="" class="" decoding="async"/><noscript><img src="https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Cowboy-Streetlight-Concealments-FPDS.png?w=620&strip=all&quality=75" alt="" /></noscript></div></div></figure><p class="a1dbe quartz">Christie Crawford, who owns Cowboy Streetlight Concealments with her husband, a Houston police officer, said she was not at liberty to discuss the companyâs federal contracts in detail.</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">âWe do streetlight concealments and camera enclosures,â Crawford told Quartz. âBasically, thereâs businesses out there that will build concealments for the government and thatâs what we do. They specify whatâs best for them, and we make it. And thatâs about all I can probably say.â</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">However, she added: âI can tell you thisâthings are always being watched. It doesnât matter if youâre driving down the street or visiting a friend, if government or law enforcement has a reason to set up surveillance, thereâs great technology out there to do it.â</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">Earlier this week, the DEAÂ <a href="https://www.fbo.gov/index.php?s=opportunity&mode=form&id=cbd0c228d1865f87bc88a949a39f4c63&tab=core&tabmode=list&=" rel="noopener">issued a solicitation for</a>Â âconcealments made to house network PTZ [Pan-Tilt-Zoom] camera, cellular modem, cellular compression device,â noting that the government intended to give the contract to Obsidian Integration LLC, an Oregon company with a sizable number of federal law enforcement customers.</p><figure class="_43d66 _21ffe _68dc3 quartz _451d8"><div class="_5fc35 quartz"><div class="_83471 _97ba0 visible" style="padding-bottom:37.58064516129032%"><img src="https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Obsidian-mission-statement.png?w=620&amp;strip=all&amp;quality=75" srcSet="https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Obsidian-mission-statement.png?w=350&amp;strip=all&amp;quality=75 350w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Obsidian-mission-statement.png?w=700&amp;strip=all&amp;quality=75 700w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Obsidian-mission-statement.png?w=620&amp;strip=all&amp;quality=75 620w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Obsidian-mission-statement.png?w=1240&amp;strip=all&amp;quality=75 1240w" sizes="(min-width: 48em) 620px, 100vw" alt="" class="" decoding="async"/><noscript><img src="https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Obsidian-mission-statement.png?w=620&strip=all&quality=75" alt="" /></noscript></div></div></figure><p class="a1dbe quartz">On November 7, the Jersey City Police DepartmentÂ <a href="https://www.cityofjerseycity.com/UserFiles/Servers/Server_6189660/File/2018%20Resolutions/RES%202018%2011%2007.pdf" rel="noopener">awarded a contract to Obsidian Integration</a>Â for âthe purchase and delivery of a covert pole camera.â The filing did not provide further design details.</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">Obsidian did not respond to a request for comment, nor did Morgan Hairston, the Department of Justice contracting officer handling the bids.</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">In addition to streetlights, the DEA has also placed covertÂ <a href="https://www.fbo.gov/index?s=opportunity&mode=form&id=a0459e93674685daf7c08cfa3db0ed2e&tab=core&tabmode=list&=" rel="noopener">surveillance cameras inside traffic barrels</a>, a purpose-built productÂ <a href="http://www.boundlesssecurity.com/documents/BoundlessSecurity_Rapid_Deployment_Battery-Powered_Covert_Traffic_Barrel_Cellular_Wireless_Digital_Video_Surveillance_System_with_Smartphone_WiFi_Monitoring_flyer.pdf" rel="noopener">offered by</a>Â a number of manufacturers. And as QuartzÂ <a href="https://qz.com/1400791/that-road-sign-telling-you-how-fast-youre-driving-may-be-part-of-a-us-government-surveillance-network/" rel="noopener">reported last month</a>, the DEA operates a network of digital speed-display road signs that contain automated license plate reader technology within them.</p><figure class="_43d66 alignnone _68dc3 quartz _451d8"><div class="_5fc35 quartz"><div class="_83471 _97ba0 visible" style="padding-bottom:82.66129032258064%"><img src="https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Traffic-barrel-with-covert-camera.png?w=620&amp;strip=all&amp;quality=75" srcSet="https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Traffic-barrel-with-covert-camera.png?w=350&amp;strip=all&amp;quality=75 350w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Traffic-barrel-with-covert-camera.png?w=700&amp;strip=all&amp;quality=75 700w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Traffic-barrel-with-covert-camera.png?w=620&amp;strip=all&amp;quality=75 620w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Traffic-barrel-with-covert-camera.png?w=1240&amp;strip=all&amp;quality=75 1240w" sizes="(min-width: 48em) 620px, 100vw" alt="" class="" decoding="async"/><noscript><img src="https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Traffic-barrel-with-covert-camera.png?w=620&strip=all&quality=75" alt="" /></noscript></div></div></figure><p class="a1dbe quartz">Chad Marlow, a senior advocacy and policy counsel for the American Civil Liberties Union, says efforts to put cameras in street lights have been proposed before by local law enforcement, typically as part of a âsmartâ LED street light system.</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">âIt basically has the ability to turn every streetlight into a surveillance device, which is very Orwellian to say the least,â Marlow told Quartz. âIn most jurisdictions, the local police or department of public works are authorized to make these decisions unilaterally and in secret. Thereâs no public debate or oversight.â</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">The impact of surveillance cameras will increase as the development of facial recognition algorithms become more commonplace among law enforcement agencies. Amazon has been particularly interested in outfitting camerasÂ operated by the US Department of Homeland Security (DHS) with facial recognition, according toÂ <a href="https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/5014186-Amazon-ICE-emails-FOIA.html" rel="noopener">emails</a>Â recently unearthed by the Project on Government Oversight.</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">âWe are ready and willing to support the vital [Homeland Security Investigations] mission,â an Amazon employee wrote in an email that touted the companyâs facial recognition software.</p></div><aside class="_81b22 _06156"></aside></div><footer class="_4a48d"><div class="_61cca e970b"><div class="