s, and company swag. But somethingâs missing here. Where are all the employees?</p><div class="b18b1 quartz">âIâll keep shouting from the rooftop because everyone should do it.â</div><p class="a1dbe quartz">With a staff of 450 spread over 45 countries, Automattic is often regarded as one of the largest and most successful examples of a fully distributed workforce. âI used to be very conflicted,â says CEO Matt Mullenweg. âAll I hear from my friends in San Francisco is how hard it is to hire. Should I not tell them this secret? I decided itâs a great idea and everyone should do it. Iâll keep shouting from the rooftop because everyone should do it.â</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">For Mullenweg, it was only natural the companyâs employees would work remotely given its roots in Wordpress, an open-source blog publishing network with collaborators all over the world. (Wordpress VIP, however, is a commercial product that powers many news organizationsâ websites, including Quartz.) âWeâve never worked any other way,â he says. While the company does pay for employeesâ coworking spaces, overall itâs saving on real estate and relocation costs, though it declined to say how much. The company insists that ultimately cost wasnât a deciding factor.</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">To make the distributed model work, Automattic, which was founded in 2005, relies on technology to keep employees in sync. Even if team members are in the same location, the company encourages meetings to take place online in the spirit of transparency. âThe worst possible thing when youâre working from home is that you feel youâre not in the loop,â says Toni Schneider, who served as CEO from 2006 to 2014. âWe want everyone else who is remote to feel completely equal.â (Like many Wordpress employees, Schneider likes to mix work with travel, as he did during aÂ <a href="https://crosscountry08.wordpress.com/">cross-country road trip</a> with his family in the summer of 2008.)</p><div class="b18b1 quartz">âThe worst possible thing when youâre working from home is that you feel youâre not in the loop.â</div><p class="a1dbe quartz">Automattic is a place with few hard and fast rules. In addition to letting staff work where and when they want, it has an open-vacation policy and urges employees to âuse your best judgmentâ when it comes to expenses, according to Ingrid Miller, who works in human resources. The company is broken up into about 70 teams varying in size from two to about a dozen people. Mullenweg describes the setup as âa collection of small startups working in harmony with each other.â Teams areÂ empowered to try new tools if they believe it canÂ help them work more efficiently.</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">A decade-plus of experimentation has led AutomatticÂ to its current set of tools:</p><ul class="_487dc quartz"><li>Slack, a business chat app used for day-to-day communication</li><li>P2, a <a href="https://p2theme.com/">Wordpress theme</a> modeled after Twitterâs stream with in-line replies for more in-depthÂ discussions</li><li>Wikis, field guides with content that rarely changes</li><li>Zoom video conferencing</li></ul><p class="a1dbe quartz">But there were many pain points before it arrived at this arrangement. Originally, Automattic used Internet Relay Chat (IRC), a text chat protocol that predates AOL Instant Messenger, for instant messaging. But with the proliferation of mobile devices, employees sought an easierÂ way to chat from their phones. Skype was far from a perfect solution, but it had a mobile app, making it one of the better offerings in 2008. The main drawback was thatÂ conversations were siloed into individual groups, which âis terrible for distributed companies,â says Schneider.</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">There was an awkward transition period where employees were expected to be on both IRC and Skype. Eventually, the company migrated to Slack en masse, but even that came with its false starts, as various teams had used and abandoned the chat appÂ before it finally stuck for good in 2014. âOur lifeblood today is Slack and [a Wordpress theme]Â <a href="http://ma.tt/2009/05/how-p2-changed-automattic/">we created called P2</a>,â says Mullenweg.</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">Slack checked off a number of boxes for Automattic. It had a mobile app, and it allowed employees to chat in public channels, privately in groups, and directly with colleagues. Still âthere were some holdouts,â recalls software engineer Kat Hagan, who livesÂ in Oakland. Some employees worried about trusting a third party with its chat logs. Plus, in an ideal world, all of Automatticâs tools would be open source. In this case, convenience won out.</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">As withÂ all chat apps, Slackâs constant pings can be distracting, and itâs easy for conversations to get derailed. To keep important discussions from disappearing into the ether, the company hasÂ a specific Wordpress theme thatÂ keeps conversations focused with threaded conversations. Created during a <a href="https://en.blog.wordpress.com/2008/01/28/introducing-prologue/">2008 company gathering in Oracle, Arizona</a>, P2 (originally called Prologue) is âlike the Wordpress equivalent of an activity stream,â says Davide Casali, a London-based designer whose team works on Wordpress themes.</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">For all the thought that went into chat, there are grayÂ areas. There are times when a discussion in Slack picks up so much chatter that it becomes better suited for P2. âWe have an emoji for thatâa P2,â says Casali. That usually prompts a person involved in the conversation to transcribe and summarize the discussion in a P2 post.</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">But subtlety can get lost in text transmission. âI would probably say the biggest breakthrough for us was really when [Google] Hangouts started to come along, and really the idea of group video conferencing all of a sudden became very doable,â says Schneider. In Automattic fashion, some teams later tried Zoom, a video conferencing chat app that displays participants in a <em>Brady Bunch</em>-like grid, and ânow weâre all sort of hopping on the Zoom train,â says Hagan.</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">Of course, video is not a complete replacement for face-to-face interactions. Some within the organization, including Mullenweg, have contemplated the role virtual reality can play in collaboration, but thatâs a faraway future. For now, itâs hard to beat the real thingâsitting across from a coworker, able to read his or herÂ body language and facial ticks in person. This is why Automattic organizes a company-wide meetup once a year in an exotic locale for a week. Teams are also encouraged to plan their own outings, mixing work and play,Â two to three times a year with a budget of about $250 per person per day, excluding airfare.</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">âWhile itâs possible to work remotely, thereâs a bonding and a familiarity that develops when youâre in person together thatâs irreplaceable,â says Mullenweg.</p><h2 class="_7d6a7 quartz"><strong>The takeaways</strong></h2><p class="a1dbe quartz">For a fully distributed company to work, everybody needs to be on the same page. Automattic believes transparency is a key part of that, and that means making conversations, documents, meetings, and leadership training sessions open to the entire company. Furthermore, as MullenwegÂ <a href="https://ma.tt/2012/09/future-of-work/">wrote in a 2012 blog post</a>, you âhave to beÂ really committed to keep the creative center and soul of the organization on the internet, and not in an office.â</p><div class="b18b1 quartz">âIf we make it look easy, itâs because weâre working incredibly hard at it.â</div><p class="a1dbe quartz">Employees are drawn to Automattic because of the companyâsÂ flexibility,Â but that can also make itÂ tough to maintain a work-life balance, something employees have to figure out for themselves. For example, Hagan, a night owl who says she works best from 9pm to 2am, will offsetÂ a particularly long workdayÂ with a shorter one. Ultimately, Automatticâs not the kind of company that feels the need to peer over employeesâ shoulders. Itâs lessÂ focused on setting rules as much as expectations that employees will get their work done.</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">When AutomatticÂ grew to 50 people and later to 150 people, Mullenweg had concerns aroundÂ how the distributed model would scale.Â MuchÂ thought went into whatÂ tools to use and how to use them. Employees, who are in small, agile teams, areÂ encouraged to experiment with different ways of working.Â Sometimes these experiments areÂ adopted companywideÂ (as was the case with Slack), and sometimes, they fail (like one teamâs attempt at Holacracy).</p><p class="a1dbe quartz">âIf we make it look easy, itâs because weâre working incredibly hard at it,â says Mullenweg.Â At this point, though, heÂ doesnât âsee an upper bound to itâ and says he âcan imagine Automattic as a company with thousandsâ of remote employees.</p></div><aside class="_81b22 _06156"></aside></div><footer class="_4a48d"><div class="_61cca e970b"><div class="_3b7f8"><div class="_5f5af"><a href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=https%3A%2F%2Fqz.com%2F694410%2F&amp;text=This%20pioneering%20tech%20company%20figured%20how%20to%20make%20work-from-home%20work&amp;via=qz" class="_1a7c0 quartz article twitter" target="_blank" rel="noopener" title="Share via twitter"><svg width="25" height="20" viewBox="0 0 25 20"><path d="M22.053 3.122A5.006 5.006 0 0 0 24.308.364c-.992.573-2.094.987-3.255 1.211A5.212 5.212 0 0 0 17.305 0c-2.835 0-5.129 2.232-5.129 4.986 0 .388.045.77.13 1.134A14.71 14.71 0 0 1 1.737.913a4.884 4.884 0 0 0-.693 2.507c0 1.727.91 3.252 2.286 4.146a5.207 5.207 0 0 1-2.324-.623l-.001.064c0 2.413 1.767 4.427 4.114 4.888-.43.112-.884.172-1.352.172-.33 0-.653-.03